# legacy-peer-deps: restore npm v6 behavior where peer-dependency conflicts are
# ignored instead of aborting the install (npm v7+ treats them as fatal ERESOLVE
# errors). This was introduced during the Nx 19->22 / Angular 18->21 upgrade and
# is currently REQUIRED — `npm install` / `npm ci` fail without it.
#
# Why it's needed (chain of events) — chokidar, the actual install blocker:
#    - The workspace pins chokidar@3, and it is dual-constrained to v3:
#        * `transloco-scoped-libs` imports it as a RUNTIME dependency and calls
#          `chokidar.watch(...)` (see libs/transloco-scoped-libs/src/lib/transloco-scoped-libs.ts).
#          chokidar@4+ removed glob support, so bumping it would break that lib.
#        * karma@6.4.3 also requires chokidar@^3.5.1.
#    - Meanwhile Angular's @angular-devkit/core@21 declares chokidar@^5 as an
#      OPTIONAL peer dependency. Even though the peer is optional and unused by
#      our build, npm v7+ strict resolution rejects the 3-vs-5 mismatch with
#      `ERESOLVE could not resolve` and refuses to install.
#    - legacy-peer-deps lets the install proceed with chokidar@3, and (critically)
#      keeps local `npm install` and CI `npm ci` resolving the SAME tree — without
#      it the lockfile and `npm ci` disagree.
#
# Caveat: this flag is workspace-wide — it disables ALL peer-conflict detection,
# not just the chokidar case above, so a genuinely incompatible peer elsewhere
# will NOT be flagged at install time. That is the accepted trade-off for keeping
# chokidar at v3.
#
# How to remove it later (both must be true):
#   a. Migrate Karma -> Vitest (drops karma's chokidar@3 constraint), AND
#   b. Move transloco-scoped-libs off chokidar's glob API so it can adopt
#      chokidar@5, satisfying @angular-devkit/core's optional peer.
# Once those are done, strict peer resolution should pass and this flag can go.
legacy-peer-deps=true
